01:50.193 --> 01:52.867
In 2009, I set out
to make a film about

01:52.988 --> 01:55.616
Lance Armstrong's comeback year.

01:55.699 --> 01:57.793
It seemed like a great ride.

01:57.868 --> 02:00.121
A retired champion
with a contentious past

02:00.245 --> 02:02.498
comes back to
cycling to show them all.

02:02.581 --> 02:05.004
Then the Lance
doping scandal erupted

02:05.125 --> 02:07.469
and I had to put the film aside.

02:07.544 --> 02:09.512
When I picked
the film back up, I faced

02:09.588 --> 02:12.592
the same question
that haunted me in 2009.

02:12.883 --> 02:14.977
Why did he come back?

02:15.052 --> 02:17.896
He'd won the Tour de
France seven times.

02:17.971 --> 02:20.645
I wondered what
I had been witness to in 2009.

02:21.350 --> 02:25.321
And what did it mean now that the
truth about Lance was known?

02:26.104 --> 02:30.484
In making my new film, all roads
seemed to lead back to the past.

02:47.918 --> 02:52.424
I viewed my battle with
cancer as an athletic competition.

02:52.631 --> 02:55.180
But in that,
you either win or you lose.

02:55.258 --> 02:57.852
When you lose,
or if you lose, you die.

02:57.928 --> 03:01.432
So I took that perspective,
which is a little dark,

03:01.515 --> 03:04.359
and I put it into everything
I've done since then.

03:04.434 --> 03:06.027
I like to win.

03:06.103 --> 03:07.543
But more than anything,
I can't stand

03:07.562 --> 03:08.563
the idea of losing,

03:08.647 --> 03:10.365
because, to me,
that equals death.

03:10.440 --> 03:13.114
Look at this. Armstrong
accelerating once again.

03:13.193 --> 03:14.754
And there's a gap
now starting to appear

03:14.820 --> 03:18.040
between Lance Armstrong
and Marco Pantani.

03:18.115 --> 03:20.083
Well, I never
thought I'd see the day when

03:20.200 --> 03:22.123
Lance Armstrong
would blow away the man

03:22.202 --> 03:24.830
we've always referred to as the
finest climber we've ever seen

03:24.913 --> 03:26.881
in the current
peloton of cycling.

03:26.957 --> 03:29.380
But there's one matter
that's stayed on Armstrong's tail,

03:29.459 --> 03:31.882
allegations he's used
banned performance enhancers.

03:31.962 --> 03:34.135
Where he's found this
strength from, I don't know.

03:34.214 --> 03:36.637
He has torn
the field apart here.

03:37.384 --> 03:39.307
The mythic nature
of his essential comeback,

03:39.386 --> 03:41.059
getting cancer and
coming back and being

03:41.138 --> 03:44.563
a great athlete,
is an astonishing story.

03:44.641 --> 03:46.439
If he's clean,
it's the greatest comeback.

03:46.560 --> 03:48.358
If he's not,
then it's the greatest fraud.

03:48.437 --> 03:50.565
I don't think any
sports team or any athlete

03:50.814 --> 03:53.033
has ever come under
this kind of scrutiny.

03:53.567 --> 03:55.569
Oh, and Beloki's gone down!

03:55.652 --> 03:57.199
Armstrong's off
the road as well.

03:57.320 --> 03:58.913
Armstrong,
complete control there.

03:58.989 --> 04:01.492
He's into the field,
but what a great bike rider.

04:01.575 --> 04:03.998
He's gone across.
This is unbelievable.

04:04.077 --> 04:05.499
I've never seen this before.

04:05.579 --> 04:07.456
Armstrong went
across the field there.

04:07.539 --> 04:10.258
He's back on the road
with four kilometers to go.

04:10.333 --> 04:14.679
Oh, this is incredible.
Armstrong is such a star.

04:14.755 --> 04:16.928
There are people
who have really been ruined

04:17.007 --> 04:20.101
because of Lance's aggressive
attempts to keep them quiet.

04:20.177 --> 04:23.021
He was an
immensely intimidating person.

04:23.096 --> 04:24.973
Thing about Armstrong,
he has the acceleration.

04:25.056 --> 04:27.275
When he wants to go into
a climb, he can do it.

04:27.350 --> 04:28.943
He has now decided,
"I want to go."

04:29.019 --> 04:32.614
You can see the yellow jersey is open...
What's happened now?

04:32.689 --> 04:33.941
What has happened there?

04:34.065 --> 04:35.362
Can he recover?

04:35.442 --> 04:36.443
He's come back.

04:36.526 --> 04:37.698
Armstrong is out
of the saddle again.

04:37.778 --> 04:40.201
He's jumping onto the
tail here of {ban Mayo.

04:40.280 --> 04:41.782
This is unbelievable.

04:41.865 --> 04:45.244
Armstrong is now one of
the world's most recognized athletes.

04:45.327 --> 04:48.251
To Americans, Lance
Armstrong is cycling's Superman.

04:48.330 --> 04:51.584
The bigger you are,
the better target you make.

04:51.666 --> 04:55.512
In any generation
of professional sportsmen,

04:55.587 --> 04:59.967
there will be guys who cheat and
there will be guys who don't cheat.

05:00.050 --> 05:02.599
This is a guy who was going
to succeed no matter what.

05:03.720 --> 05:05.768
His comeback and
storybook life have put

05:05.889 --> 05:07.937
Lance Armstrong
under a global spotlight.

05:08.016 --> 05:10.314
Armstrong has been
less successful in

05:10.435 --> 05:12.688
outracing accusations
of possible drug use.

05:12.771 --> 05:15.775
I've said it for seven years. I've
said it for longer than seven years.

05:15.857 --> 05:17.780
I have never doped.

05:21.655 --> 05:25.376
It's very hard to
conceal the truth forever.

05:26.368 --> 05:30.623
So this has been my downfall.

05:41.508 --> 05:43.010
No, thanks.

05:44.094 --> 05:45.346
There you are.
Come on in.

05:45.428 --> 05:46.429
I just walk on in?

05:46.513 --> 05:48.515
Hi. Thank you.

05:48.598 --> 05:50.066
Good to see you.
Ready?

05:50.141 --> 05:51.609
Saw you get your shoes on.

05:51.726 --> 05:53.148
We're getting my shoes on.

05:55.605 --> 05:56.857
Everybody, let's do
everything we need to do...

05:56.940 --> 05:59.034
This is where I came
back into the story.

05:59.109 --> 06:02.204
I was in Austin when Lance decided
to do an interview with Oprah

06:02.279 --> 06:04.498
to address charges
of doping in the press

06:04.614 --> 06:06.867
that had become
impossible to deny.

06:07.701 --> 06:10.921
Tonight on Nightline...
Did Lance cheat?

06:10.996 --> 06:13.249
Lance had been the subject
of a criminal investigation.

06:13.331 --> 06:16.335
He was also probed by
the US Anti-Doping Agency.

06:16.418 --> 06:18.512
Many ex-teammates
testified against Armstrong.

06:19.713 --> 06:22.557
Did you see Lance Armstrong using
performance-enhancing drugs?

06:22.799 --> 06:23.800
At times, yeah.

06:23.884 --> 06:25.386
There was EPO.

06:25.468 --> 06:27.470
There was testosterone.

06:28.555 --> 06:31.229
And I did see
a blood transfusion.

06:31.308 --> 06:32.685
Look,
at some point, people have to

06:32.809 --> 06:34.436
tell their kids that
Santa Claus isn't real.

06:34.519 --> 06:36.738
You're saying Lance
Armstrong is a liar?

06:36.813 --> 06:38.440
Yes.

06:39.149 --> 06:42.028
The anti-cancer crusader
was now portrayed as a cheater

06:42.110 --> 06:46.411
who ran a doping ring and used his
power as a celebrity to cover it up.

06:46.489 --> 06:49.584
UCI will ban Lance
Armstrong from cycling,

06:49.659 --> 06:53.835
and UCI will strip him of his
seven Tour de France titles.

06:54.164 --> 06:57.543
Lance Armstrong has
no place in cycling.

06:57.626 --> 06:59.628
We ready to go. Ready?

07:00.837 --> 07:02.180
So let's start
with the questions

07:02.255 --> 07:04.974
that people around the world have
been waiting for you to answer.

07:05.050 --> 07:09.021
For now I'd just
like a "yes" or "no."

07:09.095 --> 07:11.063
Did you ever take
banned substances

07:11.181 --> 07:13.149
to enhance your
cycling performance?

07:13.224 --> 07:14.726
Yes.

07:15.810 --> 07:19.656
Yes or no, was one of those
banned substances EPO?

07:19.731 --> 07:21.574
Yes.

07:21.650 --> 07:24.995
Did you ever blood dope
or use blood transfusions

07:25.070 --> 07:26.993
to enhance your
cycling performance?

07:27.072 --> 07:29.074
Yes.

07:29.157 --> 07:31.626
Did you ever use
any other banned substances

07:31.701 --> 07:36.081
like testosterone, cortisone
or human growth hormone?

07:36.164 --> 07:37.791
Yes.

07:37.874 --> 07:44.098
Yes or no, in all seven of
your Tour de France victories,

07:44.172 --> 07:47.642
did you ever take banned
substances or blood dope?

07:47.717 --> 07:49.719
Yes.

07:49.803 --> 07:53.979
The first few
minutes of Oprah was just riveting.

07:54.057 --> 07:58.528
To finally witness
him saying that he doped

07:58.603 --> 08:01.527
after the years and
years and years and years

08:01.606 --> 08:03.859
of just the most
amazing denials.

08:03.942 --> 08:06.320
I can emphatically
say I'm not on drugs.

08:06.403 --> 08:09.282
Neither I nor any
member of my team

08:09.364 --> 08:10.661
did or took anything illegal.

08:10.740 --> 08:13.493
We got nothing to hide. We know that.
Everybody knows that.

08:13.576 --> 08:15.749
You have never taken
any performance-enhancing drug?

08:15.829 --> 08:16.830
Correct.

08:16.913 --> 08:18.665
And to call somebody a cheater,

08:18.748 --> 08:21.922
a fraud, a loser,
to call them that,

08:22.002 --> 08:24.221
it has to be,
I repeat, has to be

08:24.295 --> 08:27.014
followed up with
extraordinary proof,

08:27.090 --> 08:29.639
and we've never seen it.

08:29.718 --> 08:32.597
It's cliche'. He looked me
in the eyes and told me he didn't dope.

08:32.679 --> 08:35.727
But when he does that,
he's got a power.

08:35.807 --> 08:37.683
It goes a long way.

08:37.767 --> 08:40.486
Any idiot with half
a brain should have

08:40.602 --> 08:43.322
been able to see
Armstrong was lying.

08:43.398 --> 08:45.526
They've been
testing you like crazy.

08:45.650 --> 08:47.251
They've been
following you, watching you.

08:47.318 --> 08:49.787
Don't the results speak for
themselves at a certain point?

08:50.613 --> 08:52.331
Hello!

08:54.242 --> 08:57.496
Lance Armstrong is a fraud.
I don't believe a word he says.

08:57.579 --> 09:02.130
I want this man to suffer.
And I say that with all sincerity.

09:05.587 --> 09:07.180
I can't believe
we all got duped.

09:07.255 --> 09:08.427
Lying jerk.

09:08.506 --> 09:09.849
The guy's a complete phony.

09:10.425 --> 09:12.098
He could've come clean.

09:12.177 --> 09:15.431
He owes it to the sport
that he destroyed.

09:15.513 --> 09:18.938
Was it a big deal to you?
Did it feel wrong?

09:19.976 --> 09:22.070
At the time? No.

09:22.145 --> 09:23.397
It did not even feel wrong?

09:23.521 --> 09:24.738
No.

09:24.814 --> 09:28.694
The prime time confession turned
out to be a bumpy ride for Lance.

09:28.777 --> 09:31.326
But it might never
have happened if he hadn't

09:31.446 --> 09:33.949
decided to take
a victory lap in 2009.

09:34.032 --> 09:36.160
And your comeback.
Do you regret now coming back?

09:36.242 --> 09:37.414
I do.

09:37.494 --> 09:39.997
We wouldn't be sitting here
if I didn't come back.

09:47.378 --> 09:50.427
The comeback.
What was he thinking?

09:50.507 --> 09:52.350
I kept wondering
about that question

09:52.467 --> 09:54.219
throughout the year
as I followed him.

09:55.637 --> 09:58.436
It's been a long time.
Will you be ready for the Tour?

09:58.515 --> 10:00.893
I'm comin'.
I'll be there July 4th.

10:03.228 --> 10:05.526
A few weeks
ago, when he first came up with

10:05.688 --> 10:07.986
the idea of a possible comeback,

10:08.066 --> 10:09.613
I was really surprised.

10:09.692 --> 10:12.992
I remember I sent him
a message back and I said,

10:13.071 --> 10:16.166
"Are you at a party?
Are you sober?"

10:16.616 --> 10:19.244
Johan Bruyneel,
Lance's team director

10:19.327 --> 10:21.295
for all seven of
Lance's Tour wins,

10:21.371 --> 10:23.214
was now running Team Astana.

10:24.040 --> 10:27.385
He reunited with Lance
to help guide his comeback.

10:29.838 --> 10:31.465
We good?
Sure.

10:31.548 --> 10:35.143
So is there a motivator
for you this time around?

10:35.218 --> 10:38.222
Is this in some way for you
to say to all the critics...

10:38.304 --> 10:41.934
It's been an interesting
reaction with the comeback.

10:42.016 --> 10:46.988
I mean, some people are curious,

10:47.063 --> 10:50.818
some people are pissed,
and some people are ecstatic.

10:50.900 --> 10:55.246
Few people in sport divide public
opinion quite like Lance Armstrong.

10:55.321 --> 10:58.370
To millions, he is
a source of inspiration.

10:58.449 --> 11:04.707
But to some, his incredible tale is
just that, incredible, hard to believe.

11:05.623 --> 11:07.876
Yet so many wanted to believe.

11:07.959 --> 11:10.178
Wherever Lance went,
he moved the needle.

11:10.253 --> 11:13.757
More fans, more money
for sponsors and promoters.

11:13.840 --> 11:16.935
Even so, the organization
that ran the Tour de France

11:17.010 --> 11:19.183
was reluctant to
invite him back.

11:19.262 --> 11:23.017
Just 10 months before the race,
the comeback was in jeopardy.

11:23.099 --> 11:25.978
The story is,
"Refused entry into

11:26.060 --> 11:28.438
"the Tour de
France for no reason."

11:28.521 --> 11:30.114
This guy is comin' back.

11:30.190 --> 11:33.410
He's never been caught,
prosecuted, busted for anything.

11:33.484 --> 11:37.034
He's coming back with the most legitimate,
credible program that there is.

11:37.113 --> 11:38.674
They won't let him
in the marquee event.

11:38.781 --> 11:40.328
I think the media
would fuckin' crush 'em.

11:40.408 --> 11:42.035
If they don't let him ride...

11:42.118 --> 11:44.246
He's gonna take so
much attention away

11:44.370 --> 11:46.418
from the Tour de
France to other events

11:46.497 --> 11:47.714
that they have to let him in.

11:47.790 --> 11:50.043
I think they may
come out of the gate and say,

11:50.126 --> 11:52.345
"Of course he can't race
in the Tour de France."

11:52.420 --> 11:54.172
Neither could Ivan Basso,
neither could Floyd Landis.

11:54.255 --> 11:55.256
They all cheated.

11:55.340 --> 11:56.341
That's not the same.

11:56.424 --> 11:58.301
They were all busted.

11:58.426 --> 12:00.303
And they think Lance is busted.
No, he's not.

12:00.386 --> 12:02.059
But they think...
He's not.

12:02.138 --> 12:03.481
They think it might be that way.

12:03.598 --> 12:04.895
L'Equipe said he cheated.

12:04.974 --> 12:06.942
He's never tested positive.
They think he has.

12:07.936 --> 12:09.404
He didn't.

12:09.479 --> 12:11.857
But L'Equipe said he did.

12:11.940 --> 12:13.817
What was the headline?

12:13.900 --> 12:15.652
Yes.

12:17.946 --> 12:20.040
"The Armstrong Lie."

12:21.032 --> 12:23.751
Long before Oprah,
"The Armstrong Lie" article

12:23.826 --> 12:28.457
offered proof that Lance's first
Tour win had not been clean.

12:28.539 --> 12:30.416
Through clever detective work,

12:30.500 --> 12:32.127
the author
discovered that many of

12:32.210 --> 12:34.713
Armstrong's urine
samples from 1999

12:34.796 --> 12:37.720
contained
a doping drug called EPO.

12:38.716 --> 12:40.468
If you consider my situation,

12:40.551 --> 12:44.556
a guy who comes back from,
arguably, a death sentence,

12:45.181 --> 12:46.979
why would I then
enter into a sport

12:47.100 --> 12:48.898
and dope myself up
and risk my life again?

12:48.977 --> 12:51.275
That's crazy.
I would never do that.

12:51.354 --> 12:53.322
No. No way.

12:53.398 --> 12:55.651
It was a bold claim,
considering how many

12:55.775 --> 12:58.028
riders around him
had been busted.

12:59.279 --> 13:01.577
And even after
Lance's seven Tour wins,

13:01.656 --> 13:05.286
pro cycling continued to
suffer from doping scandals.

13:05.743 --> 13:07.423
There are a lot of us
who wanted this to be

13:08.454 --> 13:10.377
a clean sport and a clean effort

13:10.456 --> 13:12.174
and a clean
victory and everything.

13:12.250 --> 13:15.629
But there's just too much
swirl around it constantly.

13:16.629 --> 13:19.098
Shortly after
Armstrong retired, there was

13:19.173 --> 13:21.551
this huge bust
called Operation Puerto,

13:21.634 --> 13:24.729
in which most of
his rivals got popped.

13:25.763 --> 13:27.481
If it was
the NBA All-Star game,

13:27.557 --> 13:29.317
it would have been every
player on both teams

13:29.350 --> 13:30.977
essentially busted for doping

13:31.060 --> 13:33.813
except that one
guy who just retired.

13:34.355 --> 13:36.323
Throughout Lance's Tour wins,

13:36.399 --> 13:39.869
all but one of the cyclists who
finished on the podium with Armstrong

13:39.944 --> 13:42.572
were implicated
in doping scandals.

13:45.742 --> 13:47.335
And finally,
the last thing I'll say for

13:47.452 --> 13:49.053
the people that
don't believe in cycling,

13:49.078 --> 13:52.753
the cynics and the skeptics,
I'm sorry for you.

13:52.832 --> 13:56.132
I'm sorry you can't dream big, and I'm
sorry you don't believe in miracles.

13:56.836 --> 14:00.682
After winning in 2005,
what better moment to walk away?

14:00.757 --> 14:02.805
What better moment to stay away?

14:02.925 --> 14:05.178
Why couldn't he have
just said thank you?

14:05.261 --> 14:07.639
"I had a nice career and now it's over.
Thank you."

14:07.722 --> 14:09.224
But that's not in him.

14:09.307 --> 14:11.230
And that urge to crush,
that urge

14:11.351 --> 14:13.228
to push back,
that urge to dominate,

14:13.311 --> 14:16.360
not just to be content with
winning, but that urge to dominate,

14:16.439 --> 14:18.533
is what ended up
bringing him down.

14:19.692 --> 14:22.536
Lance tried to
dominate my film, too.

14:22.612 --> 14:26.958
He had lied to me, straight to
my face, all throughout 2009.

14:27.867 --> 14:29.619
When the truth
came out, I told him

14:29.702 --> 14:32.080
he owed me
an explanation on camera.

14:32.830 --> 14:34.878
Whether he wanted to try
to make things right

14:34.957 --> 14:37.551
or whether he still wanted
to influence my story,

14:37.627 --> 14:39.721
he agreed to sit
down one more time.

14:41.255 --> 14:44.099
You vigorously
defended your reputation.

14:44.175 --> 14:47.270
Do you feel,
in retrospect, that you were

14:47.387 --> 14:50.436
protecting that too assiduously?

14:50.515 --> 14:54.395
Had the lie become too big? Did
it get out of control for you?

14:54.477 --> 14:57.572
Yeah, that's
the biggest regret of my life.

14:58.856 --> 15:02.861
Um, I'm a fighter.
I grew up a fighter.

15:02.944 --> 15:05.225
I was a fighter on the bike.
I was a fighter off the bike.

15:06.155 --> 15:10.410
And if you were in the race, I was
competitive and I was fighting.

15:11.744 --> 15:13.166
I forgot to turn that...

15:13.246 --> 15:15.965
I'd get off the bike, and whether
it's in a press conference,

15:16.040 --> 15:18.384
whether it's in a team setting,

15:18.501 --> 15:20.879
whether it's in
a personal relationship,

15:20.962 --> 15:23.090
I continued to fight.

15:23.172 --> 15:25.095
And I wanted to defend myself,

15:25.174 --> 15:30.431
and I wanted to defend the
sport, the team, my foundation.

15:30.513 --> 15:32.060
I was defending
all of these things,

15:32.140 --> 15:33.687
and I was
prepared to say anything.

15:36.686 --> 15:40.156
The gift that he has that gets
overlooked is his gift as a storyteller,

15:40.273 --> 15:43.197
his gift as a manager
of his own storyline.

15:43.860 --> 15:46.079
A guy at death's door comes back

15:46.154 --> 15:48.953
to win the toughest
event on the planet.

15:49.031 --> 15:50.874
The story brought more money,

15:50.992 --> 15:52.460
brought more attention,
brought more sponsorship,

15:52.535 --> 15:53.661
brought more inspiration.

15:53.744 --> 15:56.623
Lance became this
international cultural icon.

15:57.915 --> 16:00.043
And he had to
keep the story going.

16:01.210 --> 16:03.304
He could've ridden around the
world to raise money for cancer.

16:03.379 --> 16:05.507
There were a lot of
things he could've done,

16:05.715 --> 16:07.763
but the best story is
to go back to the Tour.

16:07.842 --> 16:10.971
By racing the bicycle
all over the world,

16:11.095 --> 16:14.190
beginning in Australia,
ending in France,

16:14.265 --> 16:17.815
it is the best way to
promote this initiative.

16:17.894 --> 16:20.238
It's the best way
to get the word out.

16:20.313 --> 16:23.943
He understood the power of
that story, and he used it.

16:27.612 --> 16:31.708
The disease, testicular
cancer, travels up a young man's body,

16:31.782 --> 16:34.786
so next stop is the abdomen.

16:34.869 --> 16:37.338
Next stop is the lungs.

16:37.413 --> 16:40.508
And the last stop is the brain.

16:40.583 --> 16:44.133
My dumb ass just
ignored symptoms,

16:44.212 --> 16:49.343
obvious, glaring, dirty
symptoms, for a long time.

16:49.425 --> 16:52.679
And it traveled all the way up.

16:52.762 --> 16:53.763
Severe headaches.

16:56.641 --> 16:58.143
Blurry vision.

16:58.226 --> 17:00.149
Coughing up of blood.

17:01.604 --> 17:04.824
Extreme pain downstairs.

17:04.982 --> 17:07.359
I read that you had a testicle
the size of an orange.

17:07.609 --> 17:09.328
That's an exaggeration.

17:09.403 --> 17:11.201
Lemon?

17:11.280 --> 17:12.781
Good-sized lemon.

17:12.949 --> 17:17.045
In 1996, Lance had
the cancerous testicle removed

17:17.118 --> 17:20.419
and flew to Indiana University
for an experimental treatment.

17:21.082 --> 17:23.210
The doctors there
thought Lance's chances

17:23.291 --> 17:25.714
of survival were less than 50%.

17:28.089 --> 17:31.093
Lance underwent brain surgery
to remove cancerous lesions,

17:31.175 --> 17:36.181
then began a special chemotherapy
program that would not scar his lungs.

17:36.264 --> 17:38.608
The immediate side
effects would be brutal,

17:38.683 --> 17:42.813
but if he survived, the treatment
would protect his career.

17:42.895 --> 17:45.523
Whatever I do in cycling, or
whatever I do in the Tour de France,

17:45.606 --> 17:48.155
or whatever I do in training, I'll
never suffer like I did then.

17:56.909 --> 18:00.664
That initial surgery to remove
that primary tumor in the testicle

18:00.746 --> 18:02.464
was a big surgery, a big cut.

18:02.540 --> 18:05.168
The cut was
probably six inches long,

18:05.251 --> 18:08.346
right up at the waist
and very physically painful.

18:08.421 --> 18:10.594
So I got on the bike and I just

18:10.673 --> 18:12.846
gently rode
around my neighborhood.

18:13.009 --> 18:15.011
That was a big day for me.

18:15.094 --> 18:17.938
And I went half a mile.

18:18.014 --> 18:20.858
And I did it in tennis shoes, and
I did it on a mountain bike.

18:20.933 --> 18:23.686
But I was on the bike.
I was pedaling the bike.

18:25.479 --> 18:30.201
All the feelings that are associated
with that, the wind in the hair,

18:32.528 --> 18:36.658
that initial sense of freedom
that a bicycle gives a child.

18:36.741 --> 18:41.963
Kids love bikes because it's the first
time in their life they're free.

18:42.038 --> 18:44.006
It's the first time when they're
not in their mom's car,

18:44.081 --> 18:46.334
they're not in Mom's living room,
they're not in Mom's backyard.

18:46.417 --> 18:47.634
They get on the bike,
they go down,

18:47.752 --> 18:48.992
they take a right, take a left.

18:49.045 --> 18:51.639
Nobody sees them.
They're completely free.

